&lt;p&gt;I have not found any workaround yet. Tried:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="alternate" type="square"&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;lt;context:exclude-filter type="regex" expression="org\.springframework\.issues\..*"/&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
without success&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also tried to declare Foo and Bar as @Component&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is related to &lt;a href="https://jira.springsource.org/browse/SPR-8573" class="external-link" rel="nofollow"&gt;https://jira.springsource.org/browse/SPR-8573&lt;/a&gt; All preconditions are described there. But 8573 is about detecting the default transaction manager, and this one here is about trying to apply both annotations (@SqlTransactional and @GraphTransactional) on the same method (which may be two manifestations of the same issue)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So, when I have a method:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;@SqlTransactional&lt;br/&gt;
@GraphTransactional&lt;br/&gt;
public User register(User user) throws UserException &lt;/p&gt;
{ .. }

&lt;p&gt;Only the SQL transaction is started. If I reverse the order of the annotations - only the graph transaction is started. That's because there is only one transaction manager in the trace (I checked with debug). Shouldn't there be two calls to the transaction interceptor(s)?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In fact, I moved from &amp;lt;tx:advice declaration of annotations, to @Transactional, and I found all these issues. It was working perfectly fine with the xml configuration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know I can handle this by moving the graph-db related stuff to another service, and annotate only that method with @GraphTransactional. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In fact at that point it becomes clear, that the xml configuration + @GraphTransactional(with the two interceptors) has been hiding a potential problem. What would be expected from the above code is essentially a two-phase commit situation, where two sources actually participate in the same transaction. If there is any failure, rollback both transactions. But in reality, it would not be the case if the first transaction is committed successfully, and the second commit() fails. So this may not be desirable as it hides potential problems. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That's why my suggestion is to do one of the following&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul class="alternate" type="square"&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;detect if two @Transactional-annotated annotations (and also xml + @Transactional with different transaction managers) are present for a method, and either throw an exception, or issue a WARN that explains why one of the annotations won't be processed. The user must know that he can't expect consistency for two independent transactions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;start the two transactions separately, but show a WARN that explains that this is not two-phase commit and the two transactions may leave the sources in inconsistent state&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

