&lt;p&gt;As of Spring 4.0.1 the same call returns &lt;tt&gt;false&lt;/tt&gt; which is due to &lt;a href="https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/commit/48909886a214265e3f2b3765bf2bf4a1c26bc791#diff-c8669649a63c74b5bb250b1ad09180fbL57" class="external-link" rel="nofollow"&gt;that change&lt;/a&gt; (introduced for &lt;a href="https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-11259" title="Add Converter implementations that convert legacy Date instances into JDK 8 date/time types" class="issue-link" data-issue-key="SPR-11259"&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-11259&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;). From the commit however, it's not quite clear why the implementation of &lt;tt&gt;ObjectToObjectConverter&lt;/tt&gt; now explicitly excludes &lt;tt&gt;String.valueOf(?)&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This problem is encountered primarily in Spring MVC, but the code is in core. If you post garbage to a field value that is converted into an enum type, you get a ConversionFailedException, whose message in turn is used as the defaultMessage property in the resulting FieldError. Trouble is, the message looks something like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;"Failed to convert from type ... to type ... for value &amp;lt;uh oh&amp;gt;"&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the absence of a message string for the error code, this is the message that gets written as the error. You can post all kinds of sneaky values and get it reflected back to the browser, including values like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;"&amp;gt;script&amp;gt;doBadthings()&amp;lt;/script&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;

